Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight, with overweight affecting 9% of the school population and obesity 5%.
Obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It demonstrates again the importance of the environment where it is grown for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obsessed children eat, for example, sausages at least twice as often as children of normal-weight families.
For dinner, more than 19 percent of the obese had eaten fries the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence."
In families of overweight children there is no habit of playing sports, which is applicable to most families today, where only 15% of children answered that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and involved nearly 900 primary school children from all over the Czech Republic.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a coincidence", which supports the General Health Insurance Company and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12,000 children from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
A proper diet and plenty of family exercise are determining factors, which significantly reduce the number of overweight and even obese children.
"Only half of the children surveyed have answered that they have five meals a day according to the regime: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet," collects one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast but with sausage for dinner
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, the details are also important, which also count, such as having a fixed time for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of school families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find out that in 10% of households nothing is eaten for breakfast.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that families of obese children consume unhealthy French fries much more frequently.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet soft drinks (70%) on a daily basis.
As a rule, more than 40% of the children surveyed do sports, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make up your diet
The next phase of the study allowed the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The food preferences of Czech children aged between 12 and 15 years, from the point of view of healthy eating, are far from ideal."
Among his favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets
“The popularity of sweet soft drinks is especially alarming,” the study’s final report warns.
As the main food, the palm takes the pasta and is closely followed by the poultry meat.
Practically, children always reject legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Change to healthy habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
"In the control group of study participants, who filled out the questionnaire after finishing the prevention program 'Obesity is not a coincidence,' there was in many cases a significant change in favor of the principles of healthy eating," the study results said.
It draws attention, for example, regarding sweet soft drinks, where many children would begin to prefer normal and running water.
Children would also choose poultry and fish for the main meal more frequently in the questionnaire and restrict consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
The stylist must also be a good psychologist, say the professionals
