The innovative IBM starts its second century of existence
If someone were to look for a term that would define IBM’s strategy with great precision, the closest approximation would be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet it has been a hundred years since its foundation.
The basis for this long-term placidity was laid by the firm’s first head, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the slogan that many of the world’s problems have a solution if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his stamp, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began to publish in 1935).
Watson was also the foundation of a carefully constructed company culture.
“For us, IBM involves long-term thinking, a continuous movement toward the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it stayed true to its basic principles, but without fear of the changes around it.
This has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We look forward to further prosperity in our second century,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current CEO, on his anniversary.
A sophisticated system
Watson, as early as the 1930s, cared for his employees as the businessman from Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American workers to enjoy paid vacations, insurance, stylish uniforms and a sophisticated compensation system that rewarded the best inventors and salespeople.
The same long-term sophistication is maintained by IBM in the customer relationship.
From the beginning, the company knew how to discover talent (being one of the first global companies to end any type of discrimination, it could choose without problems).
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy is the current plan of IBM, for which Palmisano will be replaced next year by a woman: Virginia Rometty.
She has been working at IBM for 30 years, where she has been head of sales, marketing and strategy.
During the last years IBM has participated in the so-called virtual meetings, online brainstorming, from which countless future strategies and innovations arise.
It is not surprising that ideas are left over, since almost half a million people work in the firm.
An institution with a good reputation
The fixed position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
“From the beginning, IBM has maintained a concept of an institution rather than a technology company,” says Harvard Business School economist Professor Rosabeth Moss Kanter, author of the IBM book.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company trying to solve business problems for technology users,” said George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says there is a difference between entering the business and directly creating a business.
IBM - or the "Great Green" - as it is known in the U.S. familiarly because of its logo, has in the last hundred years become one of the largest companies in the world.
It is arguably the most versatile technology company (develops both equipment and programs, infrastructure and web hosting services within a wide range of services, ranging from servers to nanotechnology).
It holds the largest number of patents of all American technology companies and five of its employees have received the Nobel Prize.
Among his inventions are the ATM, payment cards, financial swaps, bar codes and floppy disks.
This year, IBM has become the second technology firm by market capitalization (the first is Apple), when it surpassed Microsoft for the first time in 1996.
Looking to the future
Not all products and innovations have just satisfied the taste of customers and the moment (IBM did not bet on its own operating system, OS/2, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers).
“If your business is based on moving forward, you can’t emotionally anchor yourself in the past,” said Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its bases on other platforms (and equally, if they don’t work, abandoning them).
And this is the difference of the competition, Microsoft, which basically remains and always falls exclusively with Windows.
Technology of the future
In terms of sales, IBM is mainly dedicated to services, of which about a fifth are programs and another fifth equipment.
However, as late as 1990, equipment accounted for more than half of the supplier share.
As of 2000, IBM has sold underperforming assets worth a total of $15 billion. During the same period, it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future technology.
Investments have continued since 2008, when the modern global financial crisis first manifested itself.
IBM acts according to the premises of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who during the great economic crisis of 29 increased investments.
So far, IBM seems to have weathered the crisis.
The value of IBM shares since the beginning of 2008 has grown stratospherically up to 120%, the net profit of the company has not stopped increasing.
IBM’s currency is to change everything except its value.
It can therefore be expected that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will endure.
IBM History: From the Cheese Slicer to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave rise to IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous "token clock", which allows you to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint enlisted the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him manage the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are built).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During Watson’s first four years at the helm, revenue doubled by $9 million and the company’s large expansion across continents began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after nearly forty years in the boss’ chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began work on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights into space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the standard of computers of that time, came to the market with the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, in turn, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer comprehensive advice and services of high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid for these last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, "a smarter planet".
Its aim is to make more rational use of technology, although the areas have not yet been planned or the circumstances improved, for example with regard to transport and city administration.
For the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
In 1932 he opened a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world-renowned research team working with voice recognition.
