Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before he became the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy airing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a massacre in Norway in July that left 77 people dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time leading up to his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer’s tragedy, investigators wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just log in to Facebook.
“We realized it wasn’t that hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook’s cache of personal information is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific precision — the way marketers have been using it for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then directed them to ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes toward violence, and optimism about their own future.
By arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries — all without leaving office.
“It’s a whole new way of doing research,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results aren’t entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health problems to social trends as expressed in “likes,” messages on walls, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is driving a research boom, boosting the number of academic papers with the site’s name in the title to nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t get close to with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to poll people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You’d have to go through the game, and they’d never allow you access,” Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all that - you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and colleagues found that college students who talked about their drunken exploits on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of drinking problems than students who remained silent about the issue.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could control the site and step in to help a student post too many status updates with their binge drinking.
“You can’t treat a problem if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno’s co-author and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Seattle Institute for Children’s Research.
“We’ve found a way to identify at-risk children who might not otherwise be diagnosed.”
Facebook is also constantly “punching” its own population for data.
The site’s Data Team has compiled statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine’s Day, the expectation of voter turnout midway through the 2010 legislative period, and an index of National Happiness (primarily using the information that can be accessed – long-time digital freedom advocates who argue that the site should make its wealth of data available to others for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect your data offline, online is an open bar for everyone.
“I don’t think a lot of users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be looking at their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted with public Facebook walls of students.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it’s impossible to know that some of a user’s profile information and wall posts are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
That’s why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a paperweight and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There’s no substitute for going into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about the social – and a lot of the social still happens offline.”
Cold and Inhuman: Anders Behring Breivik Makes His First Public Appearance in Court
Anders Behring Breivik, the man who confessed to masterminding the two attacks that killed 77 people in Norway this summer, has described himself as a “resistance” fighter during his first public appearance in Oslo court.
“I am a military commander in the Norwegian resistance movement and in the Knights Templar of Norway,” he told a packed room of 500 people.
“I oppose the court because it was mandated by organizations that support the ideology of hate and because it supports multiculturalism.”
"I acknowledge the facts, but I do not plead guilty."
Judge Torkjel Nesheim interrupted Breivik during that monologue, because he “didn’t want to give Breivik the opportunity to use this audience as a platform for him to express his views.”
For the same reason he refused to allow Breivik, who brought a written speech in advance, to address the relatives of his victims at the end of the hearing.
Nesheim also ordered police to hold Breivik in custody for 12 more weeks, barred him from the media for four weeks, and said authorities would have to have strict control over all visits and correspondence for eight weeks.
About 30 survivors and relatives of the victims attended the hearing.
Some came hoping to look Breivik in the eye, others to confirm that he is locked up.
All attended with the aim of moving towards the conclusion.
“I thought it looked cold and inhumane,” one Utoya survivor told Norwegian broadcaster NRK.
"It was uncomfortable, but for me it was a step forward after seeing and hearing the suspect."
Dressed in a dark suit and blue tie, Breivik remained calm and professional throughout the hearing and looked journalists and survivors in the eye as he walked in and out of the building.
Despite Breivik’s bizarre notion of being part of a larger “resistance” movement, the judge determined he is not a mentally ill man, and said there is no evidence he acted with accomplices.
Some may find it comforting that the July 22 attacks appear to be the work of an extremist rather than a group of radicals.
But that doesn’t automatically ease the pain and confusion that an entire nation still feels.
“I wish it looked like a monster, but it doesn’t,” said a relative of one victim.
"It would be a lot easier if it looked like it."
7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview Shown at a Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off in advance of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was certainly a self-recognized designer, dreamer, and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flowchart junki — a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
By that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced out of Apple, and he was already hard at work on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely’s interview was used on Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during their transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly re-edited footage is the basis for Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, a 68-minute film that hits Landmark theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between the questions and the answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for precision.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely’s questions, pushing him to go faster toward the topics or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or the iPhone, there’s something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after I explained everything in detail here, it went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
“Over the years in the business, I’d always ask, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers they invariably give you are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs goes into detail about his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Bewildered by the way costs were recorded – often starting with a “standard cost” that was done by the eye of a good cover, and then adjusted with a “variable” – he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine commercial costs in detail.
On the Pope’s joke:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make free long distance calls.
It has been written extensively about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a payphone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world a half-dozen times and yelling through the pay phone and coming back a minute later to the pay phone next door,” Jobs says with a chuckle.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us, we didn’t know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious prank he and Wozniak nearly abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made him a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode-ray tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a ride to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for it.
On Improvising Innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
Early in his career, as he was selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a customer if he could assemble the whole equipment.
Working with just 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... I was yelling that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On large companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs prophetically foresaw how many industry leaders would stumble upon his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, so what?"
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision-making.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position is rotted away by people who don’t have the notion of good products vs. bad products – the knowledge of the necessary craft.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of the victory.
On innovation as artistic expression:
“There’s a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t make electrons do, glass does, robots do, factories do.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end it all comes down to taste - it stoops to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We’ve never been embarrassed about stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for computer science, I might be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas have dinner with healthcare law rivals as court accepts case
On the day that the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to consider the politically contentious question of whether they would accept President Obama’s health care challenge, two of his justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were treated at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will present the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying cry for conservative activists across the country.
The justices agreed to allow the lawsuit to proceed, and in fact a historic 5.5-hour plea is expected by March, and the outcome is likely to further cloud the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court’s decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and argue that the law should be scrapped will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. Attorney General during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement’s law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has long been dedicated to defending conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that defied the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel hours after the court’s preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees were, among others, Mitch McConnell, the top Republican in the Senate and an outspoken opponent of the health care law.
The special guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
It’s nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it’s not something that conflicts with ethical standards.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct governing the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were not, it could be said that they would fall under Canon Code 4C, which says, “A judge may attend events to raise funds from law-related and other organizations, although the judge may not be a speaker, a guest of honor, or appear on the program of such an event.”
However, Scalia and Thomas’s absolute proximity to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
“This stunning breach of ethics and indifference to the code runs counter to the demands of several magistrates that the court abide by the same rules that apply to all federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, the president of Common Cause.
“The judges were treated to a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending before the court.”
Their appearance and assistance in raising funds for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in critics who say they too easily mix the court’s activity with the agenda pushed by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas’s wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is magistrate Elena Kagan who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as the Obama administration’s attorney general when the first legal challenges to the law were filed in the court of first instance.
Her critics have pushed for Kagan to refrain from watching the case, saying she was too involved in upholding the law to now be impartial.
Kagan has given no indication that he will do so.
Boeing Receives Record $18 Billion Order
Emirates is ordering 50 Boeing 777 twin-aisle aircraft, with an option for 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliner aircraft to Oman Air, an operation valued at more than $1 billion.
It is rarely news when a company gets an order for 50 units of its product.
But it’s a big deal when the company is aircraft maker Boeing Co. and the selling price for the 50 planes amounts to a record $18 billion.
It is as large as the place from which Boeing received the order: the Middle East, a growing gold mine for future aircraft orders.
In a study released Monday, the Chicago-based company estimates that over the next 20 years airlines in the Middle East will need 2,520 aircraft worth $450 billion.
Boeing announced over the weekend its largest ever order for commercial jets for their dollar value – 50 double-aisle Boeing 777 jets.
The successful order came from Emirates airline in Dubai.
The airline also has an option to buy 20 more aircraft, which would bring the total sale price to $26 billion, Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Airshow.
Then, on Monday, Boeing said Oman Air had ordered six Boeing 787-8s, the so-called Dreamliner, which boasts spectacular fuel savings and passenger services.
The selling price for six of them is more than a billion dollars.
"This clearly has a huge positive effect for Boeing," Morningstar analyst Neal Dihora said.
"The quality of these particular customers is very strong."
Many Middle Eastern airlines are owned by their oil-producing nations.
Therefore, not only do they have the money to pay for the planes, but an increase in fuel prices - usually harmful to airlines, because it is one of the biggest costs - is not so harmful, because the country is making money with the increase in the price of oil.
That’s important because they’re less likely than other airlines to cancel or delay flight orders when fuel prices rise, Dihora said.
“They have natural protection,” he said.
The Emirates order solidifies Boeing’s leadership in the widebody market and helps keep its competitor Airbus SAS’s attempt to invade its domain with the A350 passenger jet at bay.
Boeing’s victory at the air show comes four months after Airbus said it was delaying the debut of the larger A350, which competes directly with the 777-300ER.
It delayed the debut to add more momentum after customers demanded an increase in payload and range.
Boeing Co shares rose 1.5 percent to $67.94.
The sister of Mexico’s president, apparently defeated in the Michoacán vote
Luisa Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n says drug traffickers helped her PRI opponent, Fausto Vallejo, in the governor’s race.
President Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n's sister appears to have lost her candidacy for governor of Michoacán during the violent state's elections, and she said Monday that drug traffickers helped tilt the race in favor of one of her opponents.
Preliminary results gave the lead in the race for governor of the western state to Fausto Vallejo, of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
"The intervention of organized crime throughout the electoral process and, especially yesterday, is alarming, not only for Michoacán, but for the entire country," Luisa Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n said in a radio interview a day after Sunday's vote.
“They threatened our candidates, our election workers... They seized the polls, set up barricades... and ordered people to vote” for the PRI.
The PRI ruled Mexico for seven decades until it lost the presidency in 2000.
However, it is the staging of a comeback, and the victory in Michoacán is an important step in that effort.
The PRI is hoping to win the presidential election in July.
Vallejo appears to have narrowly outpaced Calderon, who had led the polls before the election.
Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, a candidate from his brother’s conservative National Action Party, or PAN, refused to recognize Vallejo as the winner.
Silvano Aureoles, the leftist candidate for the Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD, who currently holds the governorship, came in third, a major defeat for the divided and unfortunate left ahead of the 2012 presidential election.
Aureoles also refused to acknowledge the preliminary results.
Vallejo, a former mayor of the state capital of Morelia, denied links to drug trafficking and urged the other candidates to accept the results.
Michoacán has long been dominated by drug cartels specializing in marijuana, heroin, and methamphetamines.
It is the home state of President Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, and he chose Michoacán to launch a targeted military offensive against traffickers in December 2006.
However, the violence has persisted.
A PAN mayor was killed a week before the elections while campaigning for Luisa Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, and numerous candidates abandoned local candidacies out of fear.
Although for the PRI, unpleasant as the elections in Michoacán seem, a victory will help boost the party.
The man who is supposed to represent the PRI in the presidential election, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, speaking from Washington, congratulated Vallejo and said: “I think this victory should be very encouraging, for next year.”
ADB urges Asia to help bail out eurozone
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has called on India and China to prepare to help rescue the eurozone from its sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term recession that would impede the growth of Asian economies.
Rajat Nag, director general of the Manila-based Asian Development Bank, said the world’s two fastest-growing major economies had to “do everything possible” to accelerate the economic bloc’s recovery either through the International Monetary Fund or directly through bilateral agreements.
He warned against the BRIC [Brazil, Russia, India, China] countries looking at Europe’s difficulties in an “impartial” way and said that Asia’s financial assistance along with European leadership and resources would help avert a long-term crisis in the global economy.
"We're all in this together."
“So anyone who can help Europe get out of the crisis is helpful,” he told the Financial Times in an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
“Asia may be protected to some extent, but it cannot be immune.”
“So if China and India can help, by all means.”
The European monetary union has been severely undermined by a sovereign debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy’s borrowing costs have skyrocketed dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The current sovereign debt crisis in Europe has raised fears it could push the global economy into recession and has prompted calls for major emerging economies to band together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that any support from Asia would be channelled through the IMF, but said that bilateral assistance – such as the purchase of bonds from the EU’s bailout fund, the European Financial Stability Fund – offered greater bargaining power for Europe’s Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, India’s trade minister, said that “India will do everything possible” to help the eurozone as its own economy was now suffering from falling exports and depleting inflows of foreign capital.
“No one wants the eurozone to remain unstable and turbulent,” he said.
“We have monumental challenges and we have to maintain a high level of growth.”
“It’s not an option, it’s an imperative, because where do we find employment for tens of millions of our young men and women?”
Others argue that developing economies like India have no responsibility to help wealthy Europeans when they face their own deep economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the US, said it would be politically very difficult to sell aid to Europe for India’s 1.2 billion people, of whom up to 800 million live on about $2 a day or less.
“At some point they will realize that Greeks retire at the age of 50 and go on vacation to the beaches and that won’t go down well,” he said.
Lee Howell, managing director of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India’s reserves should be used to keep the numerous, well-paid Greek public sector workers in jobs at poorly run, loss-making companies like the railways.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis threatened to have "significant knock-on effects" across Asia.
The Asian Development Bank’s forecast of 7.5 percent economic growth in Asia for 2011/12 now faces “downside risks” due to the threat from Europe.
He said vulnerable emerging markets needed to make “contingency plans” to protect themselves from a crisis and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Serious Pentagon warnings about possible defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta warmed Congress on Monday, warning that the looming automatic budget cuts could undermine national security and provoke a financial chain reaction from the halls of the Pentagon, to the battlefields of Afghanistan, to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon is already digesting the $450 billion in reductions over the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 billion or more reduction in cuts that may be imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
“The impact of these cuts would be devastating to the department,” Panetta said in a letter to Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.
He said Congress’ failure to reach agreement on the budget and its consequence, the so-called “kidnapping,” would result in 23 percent global reductions and a halt to many new projects.
“Such a large cut, applied in this indiscriminate manner, would make most of our naval and construction projects unexecutable — you can’t buy three-quarters of a ship or a building — and seriously damage other modernization efforts,” Panetta wrote to senators.
“We would also be forced to remove many of our civilian officials involuntarily and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, it is almost certain that we would have to fire civilians in order to meet the target.”
“These changes would break faith with those who maintain our military and seriously damage goodwill.”
The cuts would eventually reach combat troops, Panetta said.
“While wartime funding in the Overseas Contingency Operations accounts is not directly affected by the hijacking, wartime efforts would be negatively affected by severe disruptions in base budgets,” Panetta warned.
“The hiring of personnel would be reduced, which would lead to delays in contracts and oversight of the contract that supports the war.”
“Payroll staff would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to suppliers in wartime, and legal and political support would be disrupted.”
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for information about the possible impact of the automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
“The consequence of a hijacking at the Department of Defense would cause a rapid decline of the United States as the world’s leading military power.”
“We are firmly against this draconian action,” the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they released Panetta’s letter.
“This is not a result that we can live with, and it is certainly not one that we should impose on ourselves.”
“The kidnapping is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and must not be allowed to occur.”
Whether Panetta’s letter and recent warnings from senators will increase pressure for a budget commitment or intensify calls to exempt the Pentagon from the cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly outspoken about the potential cuts, even though he came to a job at the top of the Pentagon with years of experience budgeting in Congress and the White House and knowing that he faced tough decisions.
At a news conference last week, the secretary of defense painted a grim picture of what might lie ahead — an army with a shell, but not a core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a brigade without bullets."
“It’s an air wing without enough trained pilots.”
“It’s a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to accomplish the mission,” Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
“It is a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is not able to keep up with potential adversaries.”
"Indeed, it invites aggression..."
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta spells out new details of how the reductions “generate significant operational risks: delayed response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severely limits our ability to be previously deployed and engaged around the world; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations.”
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could face the axe, including those already being tested and some only in the early stages of planning.
That list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter fighter jet, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new littoral combat ship and the new land-based combat vehicle that the Army and Navy need to replace, the humvee.
Stopping further development and testing of the F35 could generate some $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is the vital next step in improving and addressing potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to spot a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging accusations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired soccer coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “caught” with an open microphone asserting to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
The New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist, Anthony Weiner, made a fool of himself with his denials quickly refuted by the irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating on school and college exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given test answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How deceptive are we?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, a lot of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or “locating lies,” is an essential skill that we should all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", deception detection is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been refuted.
Liars do look into the eyes.
They do not always stutter, babble, blush, or fidget.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and timing.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps you navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented lies," while women tell more "other-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- than married people lie to their partners less frequently than non-married people (but the lies they often tell tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the habitual behavior of the subject.
This is called "creating a baseline."
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally hits your foot all the time so you don’t make unfair accusations when you see your feet hitting in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for misleading, verbal, and nonverbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavior groups as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceiving people can freeze their upper body by trying to remember their history, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit “post-interview relief” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the tough questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely pretend that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used the past tense while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat may also use distancing language: "I did not have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone may use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... as far as I know... as far as I understand."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills for discovering deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
Controversial pipeline plan diverted after threat of U.S. delay in approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico -- angering unions while appeasing environmentalists -- the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is willing to redirect the project to get it back on track.
TransCanada said Monday night it will move the planned pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive Sandhills area in Nebraska, and is confident the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at a news conference at the Nebraska Capitol.
TransCanada executive Alex Pourbax says the company remains confident the pipeline will eventually be approved, albeit on a different route.
This follows last week’s announcement by the State Department that they would delay the decision on a federal permit for the project until new potential routes are considered that bypass the Sandhills areas of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, a vast groundwater supply.
“This is a real path of progress,” Rep. Lee Terry, R-Nebraska, told Fox News.
The new environmental review ordered by the State Department is likely to set aside any decision until 2013, after next year’s election, though officials denied the policy was involved in the decision.
Obama, in a statement written last week, described the decision as the State Department’s request, and expressed his full support for them.
The 1,700-kilometer pipeline would stretch from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would bring 700,000 barrels a day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
For this, it would be necessary to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, which have bet on the estimate of 20,000 jobs linked to the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan are weighing legislation to force a move away from the Sandhills region and the Ogallala aquifer, the largest source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department’s current environmental impact study found that the project posed only limited adverse environmental impacts, but the energy industry source said the department’s inspector general has ordered an independent test of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is whether TransCanada-hired lobbyist Paul Elliot, who was Hillary Clinton’s campaign adviser in 2008, represents a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a firm that was hired to run the original studio was an inappropriate choice because it was tied to TransCanada.
Patti LaBelle sued for allegedly causing a child to vomit in fear
A New York family claims that disco diva Patti LaBelle behaved like crazy in the lobby of their Manhattan building, terrifying her young daughter to the point that she vomited in fear.
The "Lady Marmalade" singer's tirade scared 18-month-old Genevieve Monk so much that she suffered "personality changes, sleep disturbances" and "increased her fear of strangers," her family says in Manhattan Supreme Court.
It was Nov. 10 last year when stagehand Kevin Monk, his wife, Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were preparing to go on a family trip.
As Kevin Monk took the car, Roseanna Monk came down to the lobby of the Riverside Boulevard building, with her luggage, carrying Genevieve.
Roseanna Monk said she stood near the door and put her daughter on the floor for a moment.
“Somebody came up behind me and said, ‘You know what your daughter is doing?’ I said ‘yes’ and I went to get her,” she said.
LaBelle angrily admonished the pregnant woman.
"He said in an aggressive tone, 'I shouldn't have left your daughter near the door,'" Roseanna Monk said.
"I said, 'I have no interest in what you say or think.'
He got angry and started using bad words - the word C and the word J out loud...
I had a bottle of water and he started to throw the water out of the bottle on me."
He said Genevieve got hysterical.
"I said to this woman, 'Look what you've done to my daughter,'" the girl's mother said.
LaBelle pounced on the mother -- who was still holding Genevieve -- and had to be restrained by her surroundings and retreated to a waiting car, Roseanna Monk said.
The little girl was crying so hard that she vomited, he added.
The family later sent a note apologizing to LaBelle, but got no response.
LaBelle’s lawyer and representatives did not return calls to comment on what happened.
The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages, but the family’s attorney, Sam Davis, said he took the case for free and that the family plans to donate all the money it gets to a cancer children’s support association.
“The purpose is to hold Patti LaBelle accountable for her conduct,” Davis said.
“That kind of behavior is completely unacceptable, especially when it’s directed at a kindergarten teacher carrying an 18-month-old child in her arms.”
Climate Adversity Curbing the Economy
During the first year of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez’s administration, unemployment and informality increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment fell and the economy contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the government of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez, self-called change, which generated great expectations regarding the progress in the economy, but given the climatic adversity at the beginning of the year, there is no growth, instead there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing millionaire losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of the overall economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historical fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost damage, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares were damaged, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent had partial damage, the main crops damaged were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a constant increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55,053 Sinaloan people were unemployed19, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the economically active population, for the second quarter the rate went from one thousand to six thousand.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for the economist Gerardo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
“What we are seeing is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the effects of a restriction of resources by the legislation that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, since for people who grab dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Detained migration
L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes pointed out that in the increase in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
“The number of people leaving the state in search of work abroad in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties to enter, and second because entering they also have many difficulties to find work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Informality
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being contributing as a worker before any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the labor lags of the state are low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Ministry of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was, until September, 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7,375 pesos.
FDI contraction
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there was the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Economy from January to June the state FDI totaled 630,697 dollars, which represents a fall of 87.74 percent compared to the 5,143,312 dollars registered during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17.28 billion pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
Faced with the scenario of economic contraction, the state government asked the state congress in July for the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, the same that would be allocated to investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2.6 billion pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdés’s government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we must work intensely to recover the ground we lost in this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, the effort of all failed to align and above all the good and synchronized progress of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic Slowness
Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said that events such as the frosts of the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining Vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he said that it is necessary to prosecute the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
“In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated,” he said.
Work to be done
The president of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better directs the Government’s efforts.
"In general terms I would say that the government has been striving to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term program is developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its way of conducting public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
