Quintet included the country in its tour of celebration of two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to play one of their best shows next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It has been more than 20 years of waiting, but the band assures that for them it will also be to make the dream of playing in the country a reality.
This was assured by bassist and founding member, Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is on the South American wing of its tour celebrating two decades of work and on Sunday 20 will make its only stop in Central America.
That day they will perform at the Estadio Nacional, starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the angeline band The X and the Las Robertas Nationals.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which is in The Nation on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican fans, it is a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica, are they aware of what their fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I have been to Costa Rica only once and on vacation; it is such a beautiful country and I think we will be able to stay a few days there.
So we’re excited to bring our music there.
I ask because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live intensely the days before.
What do you say to your most devoted followers?
Thank you for staying by our side through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even already refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played over the last 21 years happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we found out, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they have been delivering huge shows with many songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never played there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best possible show with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's this all about?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we have not played for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we could have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting to us and therefore I think it also makes it more interesting to people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all they have achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us imagined that we would be in a great rock band and having done it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of grunge?
It’s always been an honor to be part of that group of great bands.
We are very friends of the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s surprising when a move comes from a group of friends and it’s rare.
Every now and then, a gang emerges from a city, but it is much stranger when five or ten gangs leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to be friends with all of them still and we’re honored to be a part of that Seattle sound that came out.
It’s also very strange that a band like yours would stay together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is a lot longer than many bands last.
First, I think we’re all lucky to still be alive, and second, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also been opened that give everyone freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you don’t get too much touring because it’s easy to fall into that game of the big crowds and the people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you to respect the music and what brought it, not to be infatuated with being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote really good songs and at the beginning it was a great thing.
We were a band for almost three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were a lot of frustrations because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very friends of Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think about the amazing person Andy was and how it made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that is why you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band that we liked the most, so we are eager to see what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That’s a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to mind.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
There are so many.
Among the first ones that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bass players that I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant despite not being a fad anymore?
I think all of us always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all of those that came up at the same time, and, if there’s relevance now, I think it’s a wonderful thing because it’s music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that may seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs although they may sound a bit positive.
With both, when Ed touched me, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there’s some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
Peru:
Fujimori hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted Tuesday to a public hospital to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from a number of ailments, including cancer of the tongue he has been operated on four times and which remains under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Channel N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to get the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated four times from cancer to the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which have been added other pathologies such as severe erosive gastritis, cyst of the pancreas, kidney stones, hypertension and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in detention since September 2007 at the National Police Special Operations Directorate.
In April 2009 he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the death of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and made up of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political and commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans residing in Mexico, according to the agenda disseminated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "propitious for the exchange of information in all political matters between the two nations," according to the presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay’s rejection and the call for consultation with its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group made up of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, and has in force with the South American country, since January of this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the implementation of tax exchange agreements in order to leave the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), formed by countries that did not implement all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
