Park or mountain?
The architects agree on the opportunity of the call beyond controversies about fees
The municipal competition on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-1980s, in the heyday of the now defunct Corporaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration printed some promotional leaflets for Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What’s more, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York’s Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park was once again placed, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented on the north-south axis but up (mountain) -down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park results in this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with the wild boars in the role of the Yogi bear.
These were until, in September, the city council convened a mega-competition consisting of 16 contests for as many access doors to Collserola.
A door refers to the idea of a park, without a doubt.
Either that or someone is trying to put doors in the field.
The question comes up: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it means to reflect on the city is the topic of conversation among all Barcelona architects.
It is almost a recurring theme to be used when two members of this ancient caste of elect recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelona architects think, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel M<0xC3><0xB2>dol and Marta Bayona: the competition is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coastal front "it becomes necessary" to discuss "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerd<0xC3><0xA0>, that of green apples, has not been carried out.
"It is necessary to start from the base that the most extensive park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things because of its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex", says the architect for whom the title of "doors of Collserola" encloses a "lexical trap": we must not think of them "as accesses to a park, but the delimitation of areas where we have to act".
M<0xC3><0xB2>dol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, describes the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers derived from the "uncertainty that it is today to project the public space" after the experience lived in the 80s and that had in the area of the Forum "his swan song".
The first fear is the very delimitation of borders on where it can be built.
"To limit something is to fix the next step," that is to say, its overtaking.
“We have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [referring to the Metropolitan General Plan (MGP)] can lead to real disasters.”
Closer to the question, M<0xC3><0xB2>dol believes that, simplifying, the Valls side of Collserola "can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona, no", for a purely topographical question.
M<0xC3><0xB2>dol recalls that there is already a work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "should not fall on deaf ears", although he appreciates the opportunity that the city council offers his guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe-conduct that allows architects to enter the debate, but "doubts" about whether it is this technical profile that must lead the multidisciplinary teams ("a total success", he points out) that have had to be created: "Architects should be just a tool".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gives the title to this piece is complex, because the bases of the contest lack a global vision of Collserola: "16 transversal competitions have been convened - he says - in the mountain-sea sense, but there is no longitudinal reading, which sees and understands the area as a whole".
This means, at least in your case, that you have chosen to participate in the 16 contests.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors may collide in program and definition with that of the architect of the next door.
In his opinion, however, the city council should ensure that the area immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide, in all its extension, an area of facilities that would make a smooth transition between the city and the green.
