Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives
The Ministry of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results released on the accident where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter impacted directly on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that investigations made in the area of the impact do not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In a search it is reported that there are no parts or components of the craft elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
“The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport the passengers.
The terrain presents a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
At the moment, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation can last several months, even could reach a year.
Gilberto L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was operating at cruising speed and that this happened in an ascending soft terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was performed under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM located suitable conditions for takeoff, as the aircraft advances towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, there were layers of cloud at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloud conditions the crew sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the valley of Cuernavaca.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar record of the aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available so far allows us to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideways trajectory.
The pattern of dispersion of aircraft debris allows us to assume that the helicopter was hit on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
