Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that led to a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe the country has suffered since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Government of Tokyo put the material losses at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to turn the page, definitively: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rate.
