Introduction of a Budgetary "Golden Rule" in the Constitution
Austria’s ruling Social-Democratic/Christian-Democratic grand coalition government decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a budgetary “golden rule” to reduce the public deficit and thus prevent a possible downgrade of Austria’s sovereign rating by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor himself, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reached 74.6%, a figure much higher than the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were to be reduced by a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay an additional €3 billion in interest each year,” said Christian Democrat Deputy Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responds to a request from the Brussels Summit of 26 October to the member countries of the euro area: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of the public accounts in the Constitution or in a law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian government is close to the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt this type of "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease each year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, from 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal state should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is that, by 2020/2021, public debt will be reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
